{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621666"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:56:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:56:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16759"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16759"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.04,0.01,0.92]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7879"},{"type":"tags","id":"8091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9836"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22336"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThrombosis is a significant cause of morbidity and mortality. Understanding the fundamental mechanisms of blood clot formation is essential for clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the three components of Virchow\u0027s triad?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood flow turbulence, vessel dilation, and thrombocytosis","Platelet activation, fibrin formation, and clot retraction","Inflammation, vasoconstriction, and platelet aggregation","Vessel wall damage, bleeding, and clot dissolution","Endothelial injury, blood stasis, and hypercoagulability"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eendothelial injury, blood stasis, and hypercoagulability\u003C/strong\u003E. These three components comprise Virchow\u0027s triad, which describes the fundamental conditions that predispose to thrombosis. Each component increases thrombosis risk through different mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet activation, fibrin formation, and clot retraction\u003C/strong\u003E - These are steps in the coagulation cascade rather than predisposing factors for thrombosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammation, vasoconstriction, and platelet aggregation\u003C/strong\u003E - While these may contribute to thrombosis, they are not the primary components of Virchow\u0027s triad\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVessel wall damage, bleeding, and clot dissolution\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes aspects of vascular injury and fibrinolysis rather than thrombosis formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood flow turbulence, vessel dilation, and thrombocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E - While turbulence and thrombocytosis may contribute to clot formation, these are not the main components of Virchow\u0027s triad\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndothelial injury exposes prothrombotic substances, stasis allows accumulation of activated clotting factors, and hypercoagulability represents an imbalance favoring clot formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Virchow\u0027s triad consists of endothelial injury, blood stasis, and hypercoagulability as the three major factors contributing to thrombosis.","All three components of Virchow\u0027s triad increase the risk of blood clot formation, but not all need to be present for thrombosis to occur."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16759"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52274"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T15:29:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T15:29:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9450"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":